+++ b/IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md
@@ -0,0 +1,109 @@
+# User Actions Implementation Summary
+
+## Overview
+Successfully implemented the "User Action" functionality in AnkiDroid similar to AnkiMobile 2.0.88+, allowing users to trigger custom JavaScript functions from card templates using gestures, keyboard shortcuts, or external controllers.
+
+## Changes Made
+
+### 1. Core Implementation Files
+
+#### `ViewerCommand.kt`
+- Added `USER_ACTION_1` through `USER_ACTION_9` enum entries
+- Links each action to corresponding string resource
+
+#### `AbstractFlashcardViewer.kt`
+- Added `executeCommand` cases for all 9 user actions
+- Each action executes JavaScript: `if (typeof userJsX === 'function') userJsX();`
+- Added signal handling for `signal:user_action_1` through `signal:user_action_9`
+- Routes signals to corresponding ViewerCommand execution
+
+#### `card.js`
+- Added `triggerUserAction1()` through `triggerUserAction9()` functions
+- These functions send signals to the Android app via `window.location.href`
+
+### 2. String Resources
+
+#### `11-arrays.xml`
+- Added display strings: "User Action 1" through "User Action 9"
+
+#### `10-preferences.xml`
+- Added "User Actions" category title and summary
+- Added help link pointing to AnkiMobile documentation
+
+#### `preferences.xml`
+- Already contained preference keys `user_action_1_key` through `user_action_9_key`
+- These map to `binding_USER_ACTION_1` through `binding_USER_ACTION_9`
+
+### 3. UI Integration
+
+#### `preferences_controls.xml`
+- Already contained UI for User Actions preference category
+- Shows 9 ControlPreference entries for user actions 1-9
+- Includes help link to documentation
+
+### 4. Analytics
+
+#### `UsageAnalytics.kt`
+- Added tracking for all user action bindings
+- Enables usage analytics for the new functionality
+
+## Technical Flow
+
+1. **Configuration**: User configures gesture/key binding in Settings → Controls → User Actions
+2. **Card Definition**: Card template defines `userJs1`, `userJs2`, etc. JavaScript functions
+3. **Trigger**: User performs configured gesture/key press during review
+4. **Execution**: AnkiDroid executes corresponding `executeCommand(USER_ACTION_X)`
+5. **JavaScript**: WebView executes the safe JavaScript call `if (typeof userJsX === 'function') userJsX();`
+6. **Action**: Custom user-defined function runs with access to full DOM/JavaScript APIs
+
+## Safety Features
+
+- **Type checking**: Only executes if the variable is actually a function
+- **Graceful fallback**: No error if function is undefined
+- **DOM access**: Full access to WebView JavaScript context
+- **No native code execution**: Purely JavaScript sandbox
+
+## Compatibility
+
+- **AnkiMobile compatible**: Uses same naming convention (`userJs1`, `userJs2`, etc.)
+- **Backward compatible**: Doesn't affect existing functionality
+- **Forward compatible**: Supports up to 9 user actions (AnkiMobile has 8)
+
+## Example Usage
+
+```html
+<script>
+// Progressive cloze revelation
+var currentCloze = 0;
+var userJs1 = function() {
+    revealNextCloze();
+};
+
+// Show hint
+var userJs2 = function() {
+    document.getElementById("hint").style.display = "block";
+};
+</script>
+```
+
+## Files Created
+
+- `user_actions_example.html`: Complete working example card template
+- `USER_ACTIONS_README.md`: User documentation with examples
+- `IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md`: This technical summary
+
+## Testing
+
+The implementation is ready for testing with:
+1. The provided example HTML template
+2. Any existing AnkiMobile-compatible cards
+3. Custom implementations following the `userJs1-9` pattern
+
+## Benefits
+
+- **Enhanced interactivity**: Cards can have progressive disclosure and interactive elements
+- **External controller support**: Gamepads and other devices can trigger custom actions
+- **Shared deck compatibility**: Works with existing shared decks that use this feature
+- **Accessibility**: Provides additional ways to interact with card content
+
+This implementation fully addresses the feature request and provides parity with AnkiMobile's User Action functionality.

diff --git a/USER_ACTIONS_README.md b/USER_ACTIONS_README.md
new file mode 100644
--- /dev/null
+++ b/USER_ACTIONS_README.md
@@ -0,0 +1,130 @@
+# AnkiDroid User Actions Implementation
+
+This implementation adds User Action functionality to AnkiDroid, similar to the feature available in AnkiMobile 2.0.88+.
+
+## Overview
+
+User Actions allow you to trigger custom JavaScript functions defined in your card templates using keyboard shortcuts, gestures, or external controllers. This is especially useful for:
+
+- Progressive disclosure of cloze deletions
+- Showing hints or additional information
+- Interactive card features
+- Custom study workflows
+
+## How to Use
+
+### 1. Define JavaScript Functions in Your Card Template
+
+In your card template (front or back), define functions named `userJs1` through `userJs9`:
+
+```html
+<script>
+// User Action 1: Reveal next cloze
+var userJs1 = function() {
+    // Your custom code here
+    revealNextCloze();
+};
+
+// User Action 2: Show hint
+var userJs2 = function() {
+    // Your custom code here
+    showHint();
+};
+
+// More user actions as needed...
+var userJs3 = function() {
+    // Custom action 3
+};
+</script>
+```
+
+### 2. Configure Bindings in AnkiDroid
+
+1. Go to **Settings → Controls**
+2. Scroll down to the **User Actions** section
+3. Tap on **User Action 1**, **User Action 2**, etc.
+4. Assign a gesture or keyboard shortcut to trigger the action
+
+### 3. Use During Study
+
+When studying cards that have the appropriate `userJs` functions defined:
+- Use your configured gesture or key binding
+- The corresponding JavaScript function will be executed
+- Only functions that are defined and are actual functions will be called
+
+## Example Use Cases
+
+### Progressive Cloze Revelation
+```javascript
+var currentCloze = 0;
+var clozeAnswers = ["Paris", "France", "Europe"];
+
+var userJs1 = function() {
+    if (currentCloze < clozeAnswers.length) {
+        document.getElementById("cloze" + currentCloze).textContent = clozeAnswers[currentCloze];
+        currentCloze++;
+    }
+};
+```
+
+### Show/Hide Hints
+```javascript
+var userJs2 = function() {
+    var hint = document.getElementById("hint");
+    if (hint.style.display === "none") {
+        hint.style.display = "block";
+    } else {
+        hint.style.display = "none";
+    }
+};
+```
+
+### Audio Control
+```javascript
+var userJs3 = function() {
+    var audio = document.getElementById("pronunciation");
+    if (audio) {
+        audio.play();
+    }
+};
+```
+
+## Safety Features
+
+- Functions are only executed if they exist and are actually functions
+- Uses `typeof userJsX === 'function'` check before execution
+- No error if the function is not defined
+- Safe fallback behavior
+
+## Available User Actions
+
+- **User Action 1** through **User Action 9**
+- Each can be bound to different gestures/keys
+- Each corresponds to `userJs1` through `userJs9` JavaScript functions
+
+## Compatibility
+
+This implementation follows the same pattern as AnkiMobile:
+- Same function naming convention (`userJs1`, `userJs2`, etc.)
+- Same safety checks
+- Same flexibility for custom implementations
+
+## Technical Details
+
+### Signal Flow
+1. User triggers gesture/key binding
+2. AnkiDroid executes corresponding ViewerCommand (USER_ACTION_1, etc.)
+3. JavaScript execution: `if (typeof userJsX === 'function') userJsX();`
+4. Custom function runs in the WebView context
+
+### JavaScript API
+The user actions have access to the full DOM and any JavaScript APIs available in the WebView, including:
+- DOM manipulation
+- CSS changes
+- Audio/video control
+- Local storage
+- Any custom JavaScript libraries included in the template
+
+## Migration from AnkiMobile
+
+If you have cards that already work with AnkiMobile user actions, they should work with AnkiDroid without any modifications to the card templates. Only the binding configuration needs to be set up in AnkiDroid's settings.

